From: Rafly <rafly@zepharo>
Date: Fri, 10 Jul 2026 00:00:00 +0700
Subject: [PATCH] thermal: loosen trip points and soften throttle curve for
 sustained gaming performance

This patch is a TEMPLATE. The exact node names, trip labels, and
temperature values below are placeholders based on typical
Snapdragon 685 (topaz) thermal-zone layouts and MUST be verified
against your actual device tree before building.

Hosted at: https://github.com/yougotme101/extra_patches
(0001-thermal-perf-gaming-tuning.patch)

If `git apply --check` fails in CI, the node names below don't
match your tree yet — update this file in the extra_patches repo
after running the grep commands below against your own source.

--- HOW TO FIND YOUR REAL VALUES (run this first, do not skip) ---

  grep -rn "trip@" arch/arm64/boot/dts/vendor/qcom/*.dtsi | grep -A3 "cpu"
  grep -rln "thermal-zones" arch/arm64/boot/dts/vendor/qcom/

This will show you the actual .dtsi file(s) and node paths for your
tree (commonly something like qcom/topaz-thermal.dtsi or embedded
inline in the main board .dts). Replace FILE_PATH and node names
below with what you find. The values here are conservative
starting points, not a guarantee against thermal damage.

---
 arch/arm64/boot/dts/vendor/qcom/topaz-thermal-overlay.dtsi | 45 ++++++++++++
 1 file changed, 45 insertions(+)
 create mode 100644 arch/arm64/boot/dts/vendor/qcom/topaz-thermal-overlay.dtsi

diff --git a/arch/arm64/boot/dts/vendor/qcom/topaz-thermal-overlay.dtsi b/arch/arm64/boot/dts/vendor/qcom/topaz-thermal-overlay.dtsi
new file mode 100644
index 0000000..0000000
--- /dev/null
+++ b/arch/arm64/boot/dts/vendor/qcom/topaz-thermal-overlay.dtsi
@@ -0,0 +1,45 @@
+/*
+ * Gaming/performance thermal overlay for topaz (Redmi Note 12 4G, SM6225/685)
+ *
+ * Strategy:
+ *  1. Raise trip temps so throttling kicks in later (hotter allowed skin/SoC temp)
+ *  2. Widen hysteresis so the governor doesn't yo-yo between throttle steps
+ *  3. Reduce the number of intermediate mitigation steps so frequency drops
+ *     are less aggressive per step (softer curve, not a cliff)
+ *
+ * !!! You must confirm the node label (&cpu_thermal / &cpuss-0-thermal /
+ * similar) and trip-point names against your own tree's base thermal dtsi
+ * before this will apply cleanly. This is a merge overlay, not a blind sed.
+ */
+
+&cpuss0_alert0 {
+	temperature = <95000>;   /* was likely ~85000 (85C); raised to 95C */
+	hysteresis = <5000>;     /* was likely ~2000; widened to reduce yo-yo throttling */
+};
+
+&cpuss0_alert1 {
+	temperature = <103000>;  /* was likely ~95000 (95C) */
+	hysteresis = <5000>;
+};
+
+&cpuss0_crit {
+	/* Keep the hard shutdown/critical trip UNCHANGED for safety.
+	 * Do NOT raise this value — it exists to prevent permanent
+	 * hardware damage, not just performance throttling. */
+	temperature = <115000>;
+	hysteresis = <2000>;
+};
+
+&msm_gpu_thermal {
+	trips {
+		gpu_alert0 {
+			temperature = <90000>;  /* was likely ~80000 */
+			hysteresis = <5000>;
+		};
+	};
+};
+
+/* Reduce mitigation aggressiveness: fewer freq-step drops per trip crossing.
+ * If your tree uses cooling-maps with multiple cooling-device entries per
+ * trip, comment out (don't delete) intermediate steps rather than the
+ * final/highest one, so there's still a safety net. */
